\section*{Sources and Inspiration}

\subsection*{Maho Shoujo}

\subsubsection*{Sailor Nothing}

Sailor Nothing is one of the oldest deconstructions, and also reconstructions, of the magical girl genre. Sailor Nothing sets itself apart from many of the later deconstructions by showing the horror inherent in the concept of young girls fighting monsters rather than relying on some dark secret at the heart of the magical girl powers. With the focus given to mundane evils and the importance of friendship Sailor Nothing is perhaps the quintessential inspiration for Princess. It inspired us when we wrote Princess and we hope it will inspire you as well. 

\subsubsection*{Mai-Otome}

Mai-Otome takes the magical girl genre into places it does not normally venture: Politics. At heart Mai-Otome is about two girls (one a literal princess) forced to grow up by the harsh realities of Realpolitik, and in the process learning that being a magical girl is so much more than looking amazing. With friendship, growing up, magical girls and Realpolitik Mai-Otome serves well as an inspiration for Princess: the Hopeful. 

\subsubsection*{Puella Magi Madoka Magica}

As one of the most popular Maho Shoujo to be created in recent years this list cannot be complete without a mention of Puella Magi Madoka Magica. The truth at the heart of the Puella Magi makes it harder to use Madoka for inspiration but around the edges, those Puella Magi who never learn the truth, show all the struggles and heartache you might find in a Princess. 

\subsection*{Film}

\subsubsection*{Brave} 

A story about a rebellious princess with a difference. It shows the consequences when a princess rebels against her obligations; that alone makes it a worthwhile inspiration for Princess: the Hopeful. The themes of growing up and the importance of family only sweeten the deal. 

\subsubsection*{Coraline}

Coraline falls under the archetype of \textquotedblleft girls underground\textquotedblright\, stories. This archetype provides themes for the Dreamlands and for that purpose Coraline does not disapoint. Coraline's adventures help her to grow as a person and she returns better able to face the real world. Her antagonist also provides the quintessential inspiration for a Warden. 

\subsubsection*{Peter Pan}

Another girls underground story, Peter Pan (the live action film released in 2001) is a brilliant portrayal of what we fear about growing up and why we overcome those fears. It can serve as an inspiration metaphorically or more literally to show why living a utopian life in the Dreamlands isn't always the perfect choice. Not even for Beacons who have no royal duties to call them back. 

\subsection*{Literature}

\subsubsection*{Animorphs}

A story about teenagers thrust into a galactic war. Animorphs chronicles the accumulating effects of fear and paranoia on it's protagonists. A fitting inspiration for Princess. 


\section*{Lexicon}

\begin{itemize}
  \item Alhambra: The last physical remains of the Kingdom, located somewhere outside of Earth and sustained by stealing hope from the world. 
  \item Beacon: A human with enough kindness and optimism to attract a tiny fragment of the Light.
  \item Belief: A Princess' ideals, principals, and hope that the world can be saved.
  \item Bequest: A magical item that grants the wielder access to a Charm. Only Beacons, Princesses, Shikigami, and Sworn may use a Bequest. 
  \item Blessed Place: A place where a great good has taken place, people within feel uplifted and discover themselves to be more capable. 
  \item Calling: The method by which a Princess attempts to help the world. 
  \item Cataphractoi: Rare and powerful creatures of the Darkness. Cataphractoi are ocasioanlly created when a human commits suicide, and attempt to mimic habits from that person's life. Cataphractoi have little sense of self and an innate ability to command Darkspawn, so they often end up leading Darkspan in their activities. 
  \item Champion: Princesses who seek to help the world through their own physical prowess. This often, but does not have to, mean by fighting evil. 
  \item Charm: A magic spell that a Princess may learn and use. 
  \item Commonality: The strength of the emotional bond between a group. A Princess may use some Charms upon an entire group, the stronger the bond the easier it is to do so. 
  \item Crawlspace: The astral representation of a Princess' own mind and soul. A Crawlspace is always uncomfortable and hard to traverse because one use of the Crawlspace is a passage to the Dreamlands, and the Princess' subconscious tries to warn her away from The Trap (even though the trap is no longer functional). 
  \item Darkened: A human infected by the Darkness, they may wield dark magic and risk loosing their humanity. Darkened may be cured by Charms or by rebuilding their Integrity. 
  \item Darkness, the: A force of despair, cruelty, decay and corruption. Little is known about what the Darkness actually is. 
  \item Darkspawn: The most common minion of the Darkness. Darkspawn are animalistic and always evil. They cannot be cured, and must be slain. 
  \item Dethroned: A Princess who has abandoned all hope and become a warped and twisted monster. Most Dethroned live in isolation and suffering, but occasionally they can become a terrifying danger to humans and Princesses alike. Dethroned can be redeemed with great difficulty. 
  \item Dreamlander: A native of the Dreamlands. Most are a personification of something from humanity's collective unconscious though all sorts of other creatures have ended up settling in the Dreamlands, including the souls of most of the Kingdom's inhabitants. 
  \item Dreamlands: The collective unconscious of all humanity, as perceived by Princesses. 
  \item Dual Identity: An innate magical effect common to all Princesses, dual identity makes it exceptionally difficult to connect a Princess' mundane and transformed identities. 
  \item Echo: A side effect of a Princess' Inner Light, an Echo makes her actions more noticable and emotionally impactful, for good or ill. 
  \item Embassy: The Z-Splat of Princess: the Hopeful. Princesses join an Embassy by accepting a foreign concept into their own magic, most do so because they wish to redeem that concept. 
  \item Enlightened, the: Another term for Princesses. 
  \item Gales: A natural feature of the Dreamlands which warps the mind and memories of anyone who stays in the Dreamlands too long. The Trap worked by keeping the inhabitants of the Kingdom in the Dreamlands long enough to be affected by the gales. 
  \item Goalenu: A part of the Queen of Storms given temporary independence to serve her will. Goalenu are ephemeral beings, but may inhabit specially crafted bodies. 
  \item Grace: Princesses who seek to help the world through encouragement or leadership. 
  \item Inner Light: The overall strength of a Princess' magic. 
  \item Intimacy: The strength of the emotional bond between a Princess and another. A Princess may use some Charms at distance over an intimate bond, and the stronger the bond the easier it is to do so. 
  \item Invocation: The philosophical ideals of a Queen. A Princess who acts in accordance with an Invocation may strengthen her Charms and unlock new potential Charms. 
  \item Kingdom, the: The nations ruled by the Queens before the fall. Commonly held to be as close to utopian as humanly possible.
  \item Light, the: A force of hope and virtue responsible for the existence of Princesses. Little is known about what the Light actually is.
  \item Luminous Beat: One fifth of a Luminous Experience. 
  \item Luminous Experience: A unique source of Experience available to Princesses. Princesses earn Luminous Experience through helping others.
  \item Mender: Princesses who seek to help the world by healing physical or mental sickness. 
  \item Mnemosyne: The most human minion of the Darkness. Mnemosyne favour using social acumen to corrupt or torment people. Though intelligent, they have absolutely no humanity or morality and cannot be cured, they must be slain. 
  \item Noble: Another term for Princesses. 
  \item Outer Darkness, the: Another term for The Darkness. 
  \item Palace: A place to which a Princess feels a great emotional bond. Some Charms are more effective when used upon a Palace. Palace may also coloqualiy refer to anywhere a Princess lives. 
  \item Perfected self: Another name for a Princess' transformed self. 
  \item Phylactery: A physical item that represents a Princess' Beliefs. A Princess must use her Phylactery to transform. 
  \item Practical Magic: A magical ability that a Princess may use even when not transformed. Each Court provides a different form of Practical Magic. 
  \item Prince: A male Princess. 
  \item Princess: A human touched by the Light who may transform into a perfected magical self. Only people of great virtue with a strong drive to improve the world may become Princesses, however after doing so they will reincarnate upon death and reclaim their power even without living up to the standards of their first life.
  \item Protectorate: Embassies staffed exclusively by the Court of Tears. Where as Embassies wish to redeem, Protectorates wish to rule. 
  \item Queen: A Princess who has mastered her magic, completed her character development, and become the beloved leader of a nation's worth of people. Queens are significantly more powerful than Princesses, and their very existence empowers an Invocation. 
  \item Radiant Court: The Court of: Clubs, Diamonds, Hearts, Spades or Swords. 
  \item Royal Favour: A unique benefit granted to the Court of Storms whereby the Queen of Storms will enact a Charm through one of her followers, at the cost of that follower's health and possibly their life. 
  \item Seeker: Princesses who seek to help the world by uncovering knowledge. 
  \item Sensitivity: The key drawback to being a Princess being sensitive to emotional shocks, which can send her magic haywire. 
  \item Shadows: The lasting negative effects of an emotional shock, which can dampen a Princess' power and cause severe issues if they grow unchecked. 
  \item Shikigami: A Dreamlander granted a physical body so that they may assist and advise Princesses. Most Shikigami come from a Radiant Court, but any Dreamlander can become a Shikigami. 
  \item Stormwracked: A Sworn of Storms, noteably Stormwracked are usually created directly by the Queen of Storms and often act independently from Princesses. 
  \item Sworn: A human bestowed power by a Princess. Sworn often serve as assistants or support to Princesses. 
  \item Tainted Places: Areas where acts of evil have been committed. They inflict penalties upon everyone except the Darkness' minions within, and humans who suffer a Breaking Point within risk becoming Darkned. Tainted Places must be purified or destroyed. 
  \item Transformed Identity: What a Princess becomes by transforming, in this form she has greater skill, ability, and may use Charms. 
  \item Trap, the: The Trap was a powerful illusion constructed within the Dreamlands. It trapped the five Radiant Queens and their followers for millennia. Currently the trap is barely functional.
  \item Troubadour: Princesses who seek to help the world through art. 
  \item Twilight Court: The Court of: Tears, Storms or Mirrors. Members of Twilight Courts have greater benefits than members of Radiant Courts, but they pay a practical and moral price for this benefit.
  \item White Rabbit: A message created by a Princess' subconscious to alert her that she should see something in the Dreamlands. Most commonly White Rabbits lead to an event in the Dreamland that portents a future event on Earth. 
  \item Wisp: Perfectly ordinary human emotional energy, Princesses use it to feul their magic. 
\end{itemize}